  "prompt": "What exactly is the normal reaction?",
  "response": "The normal reaction, often denoted as N or R, is a force that acts perpendicular to the surface of contact between two objects. Here are its key characteristics:\n\n1. Direction\n- Always perpendicular to the surface\n- Opposes the weight or gravitational force acting on an object\n- Prevents objects from penetrating each other's surfaces\n\n2. Origin\n- Arises from the contact between two surfaces\n- Caused by the electromagnetic repulsion between atoms of the surfaces\n\n3. Magnitude\n- Depends on the weight of the object and the surface's properties\n- Can vary based on other forces acting on the object\n\n4. Examples\n- A book resting on a table experiences a normal reaction equal to its weight\n- A person standing on the ground experiences a normal reaction from the ground surface\n- A car tire on the road surface experiences a normal reaction\n\n5. Role in Physics\n- Important in calculating friction\n- Essential in analyzing static and dynamic equilibrium\n- Used in solving problems involving contact forces\n\nThe normal reaction is a fundamental concept in mechanics and plays a crucial role in understanding how objects interact with surfaces.",
